{:id "war-machine/spatial-over-tabular"
 :claim "A spatial display that shows state as shape and colour earns inhabitation; a tabular display that encodes state as numbers in rows becomes wallpaper."
 :ground "The futon2 ant war visualiser is watched. The futon0 joe-hud markdown tables are invoked on demand but require line-by-line reading and mental synthesis. A brain MRI shows which regions are active at a glance — no one reads a table of voxel intensities. The same information, presented spatially, becomes obvious; presented tabularly, becomes homework."
 :warrant "Human vision processes spatial layout pre-attentively: colour, size, position, and motion are perceived before conscious reading begins. Tables require serial processing — left to right, row by row. For a strategic overview that must be grasped quickly and revisited often, spatial layout earns repeated use because the cost of comprehension is lower on every visit."
 :backing "The ant war grid shows colony health, foraging efficiency, and territorial control without reading a single number. Churchill's war room used maps with pins, not spreadsheets. Air traffic control uses radar displays, not flight tables."
 :qualifier "Tables are better for precise lookup (exact commit counts, specific dates). The spatial view supplements rather than replaces tabular data — the table is the fallback renderer."
 :rebuttal "A spatial display can be misleading if the layout algorithm distorts relationships. Force-directed graphs can make unrelated nodes appear close. The layout must be semantically grounded (workstream clusters, sorry gravity) not arbitrary."
 :tension "Strategic information is available but encoded in tables that require effortful reading."
 :resolution "Present the same data spatially — active regions glow, neglected regions dim, imbalances are visible as asymmetric shapes. Tables remain available as drill-down."}
